bib_record.title: Cumulative fission yields of short-lived isotopes under natural-abundance- boron-carbide-moderated neutron spectrum

free_txt: Production of fission fragments at
each mass number for samples composed of 235U and 239Pu
presented in atoms/mu-g (Fig.2).
Experiment performed at 1 MW TRIGA
thermal research reactor at Washington State University
Coincidence summing correction was applied
Gamma spectra of fission products were
detected using HPGe detectors
Total uncertainty
Combined uncertainty from statistics,
gamma detector calibration and nuclear decay data
Uncertainty in neutron spectrum
Uncertainty in coincidence summing effects
Experiment performed at 1 MW TRIGA
thermal research reactor at Washington State University
Samples were irradiated in a natural boron carbide
(B4C) shield. The shield was a hollow cylinder (5 cm
outer diameter and 12 cm height), weighing 577.6 g.
The hollow center (1 cm diameter x 8 cm high) was
accessible by separating the two halves. Experimental
measurements of the neutron flux were performed using
the high-purity fluence monitors.
The experimental measurements and the MCNP model were
used as input into the STAYSL PNNL code that provided
an experimentally adjusted neutron spectrum. The
neutron spectrum incident upon the samples within the
boron carbide capsule is a soft fission spectrum at
>0.1 keV and with a weak tail extending into the
upper end of the resonance region.
A boron carbide capsule tailored the neutron spectrum,
creating a spectrum with an average energy of 700 keV,
similar to fast reactor spectra and approaching that
of 235U fission
Activation method was used
